{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489664"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"714"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/714"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.07,0.01,0.42,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90287"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/714"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74540"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"9148"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30958"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90287"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents with a four-month history of intermittent perineal pain and soiling. He is otherwise in good health and migrated from Sudan six months earlier. Examination shows a low anal fistula in the posterior position. Nothing else abnormal is found.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crohn\u0027s disease","Actinomycosis","Chlamydia","Anal crypt infection","Schistosomiasis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnal fistula is an abnormal connection between the anus and the skin. This leads to a pathological opening from where leakage of stools can occur. The large majority of anal fistulae arise from \u003Cstrong\u003Eanal crypts which have become infected\u003C/strong\u003E (eg, perianal abscess). Whilst there are other conditions - such as Crohn\u0027s disease, actinomycosis, and Chlamydia (eg, lymphogranuloma venereum) - that may be associated with anal fistula formation, most are a result of local sepsis. A few other causes of anal fistula are radiation proctitis and malignancy. Besides, this patient is otherwise in good health whereas in Crohn\u0027s disease he might have concomitant malabsorption symptoms (eg, steatorrhoea, fat-soluble vitamin deficiency) and chlamydia may have associated painful inguinal lymphadenopathy and watery discharge from the urethra. Actinomycosis associated with anal fistula is an extremely rare finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntestinal schistosomiasis is associated with abdominal pain, bloody stools, diarrhoea, and strictures. This patient does not have any other symptoms except perineal pain and soiling. Besides, intestinal schistosomiasis is a less likely cause of anal fistulae as compared to anal crypt infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most anal fistulae occur secondary to anal crypt infection."],"references":["Shawki S, Wexner SD. Idiopathic fistula-in-ano. World J Gastroenterol. 2011 Jul 28;17(28):3277-85. doi: 10.3748/wjg.v17.i28.3277."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74540"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"714"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74540"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T16:18:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T16:18:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"d